"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457954","HM Treasury","false","2016-03-21","<p>The information requested is not available in this format.</p><p> </p><p>HM Revenue and Customs publishes estimates of the tax gap each year. The latest edition was published on 22 October 2015 and is available on the gov.uk website.</p><p> </p><p>Estimates are made for all major taxes, including corporation tax and income tax. However, this information is not broken down in such a way that can be used to identify the loss of tax receipts due to the tax regimes requested.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord O'Neill of Gatley","HL6770 ; HL6771","2016-03-21T17:49:50.103Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457954/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Neill of Gatley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457954/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457954/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-03-07","Taxation","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what estimate they have made of the impact of tax regimes in each Crown Dependency and British Overseas Territory on tax receipts from individuals.","false","Biography information for Baroness Kinnock of Holyhead",,"Baroness Kinnock of Holyhead","HL6772"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457955","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-03-21","<p>Our relationship with the United Arab Emirates allows us to discuss a range of important issues, including human rights. If we have concerns regarding arrests, convictions or sentencing we make these clear to Emirati authorities as part of our broader strategic engagement.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-03-21T13:26:55.76Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457955/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457955/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457955/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-03-07","United Arab Emirates: Political Prisoners","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they have raised the treatment of political prisoners with the government of the United Arab Emirates.","false","Biography information for Baroness Kinnock of Holyhead",,"Baroness Kinnock of Holyhead","HL6773"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457956","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-03-21","<p>The National League for Democracy, which is due to lead the incoming Government in Burma, made the peace process and political dialogue its primary manifesto pledge. The peace process is also a priority for the UK. We are providing £19 million over five years to the Peace Support Fund and, with a £5 million contribution, the UK is also the largest donor and currently chair of the multinational Joint Peace Fund. We stand ready to provide further assistance to the incoming government as requested.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-03-21T13:28:06.233Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457956/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457956/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457956/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-03-07","Burma: Ethnic Groups","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the Women’s League of Burma’s call for the National League for Democracy to focus on bringing peace to the ethnic states.","false","Biography information for Baroness Kinnock of Holyhead",,"Baroness Kinnock of Holyhead","HL6774"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457957","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-03-21","<p>The Government of Burma’s term of office expires on 30 March. It will be for the incoming government, led by the National League for Democracy (NLD), to formally announce its policies when it takes office. Resource issues will be a major issue for any new government. The NLD made a manifesto pledge to distribute the proceeds of resource extraction fairly, to address the issue of environmental degradation associated with this industry and to raise labour safety standards. The UK already supports work on public financial management in Burma. We have also actively supported Burma’s candidacy for the Extractive Industries Transparency Initiative. We stand ready to work with the incoming government on resource issues at its request.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-03-21T13:29:30.82Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457957/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457957/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457957/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-03-07","Burma: Ethnic Groups","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of whether the government of Burma plans to (1) protect resources in ethnic areas in Burma, and (2) press for a moratorium on large-scale extraction projects.","false","Biography information for Baroness Kinnock of Holyhead",,"Baroness Kinnock of Holyhead","HL6775"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457958","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-03-21","<p>Gibraltar’s economy is strengthened by the UK’s EU membership. As the Chief Minister of Gibraltar has clearly stated, an UK exit from the EU would pose &quot;an existential threat in economic terms&quot; to the territory.</p><p>The UK will continue to defend and support Gibraltar’s interests, and uphold British sovereignty. The UK will never enter into arrangements under which the people of Gibraltar would pass under the sovereignty of another State against their wishes. Furthermore, the UK will not enter into any process of sovereignty negotiations with which Gibraltar is not content.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-03-21T13:34:16.383Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457958/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457958/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457958/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-03-07","Gibraltar: UK Membership of EU","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the consequences for Gibraltar of the UK's withdrawal from the EU, and what action they intend to take in relation to Gibraltar in the event of such a withdrawal.","false","Biography information for Lord Luce",,"Lord Luce","HL6776"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457959","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-03-24","<p>The Channel Islands and the Isle of Man have a special relationship with the EU, provided under Protocol 3 to the UK’s Treaty of Accession to the European Community. The procedure governing a country’s departure from the EU is set out in Article 50 of the Treaty on European Union. This provides for a period of two years for the negotiation of exit terms. After two years, the departing Member State is deemed to have left the EU, meaning that both the rights and the obligations that derive from membership would lapse. This two year deadline can be extended, but only by unanimous agreement of all EU Member States.</p><p>At the February European Council the Government negotiated a new settlement, giving the UK special status in a reformed EU. The Government's position, as set out by the Prime Minister, my Rt Hon. Friend the Member for Witney (Mr Cameron), to the House of Commons on 22 February, is that the UK will be stronger, safer and better off remaining in a reformed EU.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-03-24T15:40:44.507Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457959/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457959/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457959/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-03-07","Crown Dependencies: UK Membership of EU","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the consequences for the Channel Islands and the Isle of Man of the UK's withdrawal from the EU, and what action they plan to take to protect the Channel Islands and the Isle of Man in the event of such a withdrawal.","false","Biography information for Lord Luce",,"Lord Luce","HL6777"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457960","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-03-21","<p>The Government is considering all relevant advice and material, including the recent independent feasibility study published in February 2015, and the results of the public consultation, published in January this year. The consultation period has now ended. The Government hopes to make a decision soon.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-03-21T13:26:38.36Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457960/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457960/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457960/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-03-07","Ilois: Resettlement","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government when they plan to make a decision on the resettlement and future of the Chagossian people, and whether Parliament will be consulted in advance of that decision.","false","Biography information for Lord Luce",,"Lord Luce","HL6778"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457961","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-03-21","<p>It is for the Republic of Cyprus to decide on its external relations. Given the threats facing the Eastern Mediterranean, the need for improved co-operation across the whole region remains crucial. A Cyprus settlement would provide an important boost for regional stability. The UK commends President Anastasides and Mr Akinci for their positive leadership in the Cyprus settlement talks. As the Foreign Secretary, my Rt Hon. Friend the Member for Runnymede and Weybridge (Mr Hammond), made clear during his visits to Cyprus last year, the UK will continue to do whatever we can to support the efforts of both communities, and their leaders, to seize the historic opportunity that exists to reunite Cyprus.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns","HL6780 ; HL6781 ; HL6782","2016-03-21T13:35:04.67Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457961/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457961/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457961/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-03-07","Cyprus: Politics and Government","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of whether President Anastasiades’ approach to President el-Sisi on the basis of strategic military co-operation, to President Putin on similar issues, and to Israel on oil exploration, while claiming commitment to bilateral negotiations with Turkish Cypriots are a contravention of that procedure.","false","Biography information for Lord Maginnis of Drumglass",,"Lord Maginnis of Drumglass","HL6779"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457962","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-03-21","<p>It is for the Republic of Cyprus to decide on its external relations. Given the threats facing the Eastern Mediterranean, the need for improved co-operation across the whole region remains crucial. A Cyprus settlement would provide an important boost for regional stability. The UK commends President Anastasides and Mr Akinci for their positive leadership in the Cyprus settlement talks. As the Foreign Secretary, my Rt Hon. Friend the Member for Runnymede and Weybridge (Mr Hammond), made clear during his visits to Cyprus last year, the UK will continue to do whatever we can to support the efforts of both communities, and their leaders, to seize the historic opportunity that exists to reunite Cyprus.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns","HL6779 ; HL6781 ; HL6782","2016-03-21T13:35:04.733Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457962/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457962/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/457962/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-03-07","Cyprus: Politics and Government","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether there is any viable evidence that President Anastasiades’ current negotiations with President el-Sisi, with President Putin and with Prime Minister Netanyahu are taking place based on agreement among the current parties participating in the Cyprus peace talks.","false","Biography information for Lord Maginnis of Drumglass",,"Lord Maginnis of Drumglass","HL6780"
