"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458107","Department of Health","false","2016-03-15","<p>The respondents to the contaminated blood compensation consultation are not required to identify their association with any group. The Government response to the consultation will set out the number of respondents from specific patient groups, where that information has been provided.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2016-03-15T14:03:34.773Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458107/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458107/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458107/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-03-07","Blood: Contamination","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what representations he has received from patient groups on the contaminated blood compensation consultation.","false","Biography information for Mr Nicholas Brown","Newcastle upon Tyne East","Mr Nicholas Brown","29901"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458108","Department of Health","false","2016-03-15","<p>The commissioning of most health services for children is the responsibility of local clinical commissioning groups. NHS England has the role of commissioning the specialised services which patients with tuberous sclerosis access. In addition clinical policies are developed for new treatments that potentially change the impact of the disease.</p><p> </p><p>NHS England has approved, as an in year service development, the routine commissioning of Everolimus for angiomyolipomas associated with tuberous sclerosis. The policy statement will be published in the next few days which will define the clinical criteria for which access is supported.</p><p> </p><p>A full clinical policy for the use of Everolimus for subependymal giant cell astrocytoma is currently out for public consultation. This policy proposition will be considered for investment in the annual prioritisation round in June 2016.</p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman","29900","2016-03-15T12:25:46.807Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458108/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458108/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458108/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-03-07","Tuberous Sclerosis: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what support his Department gives to children with tuberous sclerosis complex.","false","Biography information for Greg Mulholland","Leeds North West","Greg Mulholland","29899"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458109","Department of Health","false","2016-03-15","<p>The commissioning of most health services for children is the responsibility of local clinical commissioning groups. NHS England has the role of commissioning the specialised services which patients with tuberous sclerosis access. In addition clinical policies are developed for new treatments that potentially change the impact of the disease.</p><p> </p><p>NHS England has approved, as an in year service development, the routine commissioning of Everolimus for angiomyolipomas associated with tuberous sclerosis. The policy statement will be published in the next few days which will define the clinical criteria for which access is supported.</p><p> </p><p>A full clinical policy for the use of Everolimus for subependymal giant cell astrocytoma is currently out for public consultation. This policy proposition will be considered for investment in the annual prioritisation round in June 2016.</p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman","29899","2016-03-15T12:25:46.877Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458109/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458109/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458109/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-03-07","Tuberous Sclerosis: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, if he will take steps to ensure that access to Everolimus for children with tuberous sclerosis complex-related kidney tumours is included in the NHS England draft commissioning policy on that drug.","false","Biography information for Greg Mulholland","Leeds North West","Greg Mulholland","29900"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458110","Department of Health","false","2016-03-10","<p>Data on accident and emergency (A&amp;E) attendances, emergency admissions, and performance against the A&amp;E waiting time standard is not published for individual hospital sites. The data is published at trust level only, and this information is available at the links provided in the response to question <a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-questions-answers/?page=1&amp;max=20&amp;questiontype=AllQuestions&amp;house=commons%2clords&amp;uin=28945" target="_blank">28945</a>.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2016-03-10T17:14:42.467Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458110/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458110/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458110/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-03-07","Royal Free London NHS Foundation Trust","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, pursuant to the Answer of 3 March 2016 to Question 28945, what the statistics referred to in that question were for (a) Barnet Hospital, (b) Chase Farm Hospital and (c) Royal Free Hospital.","false","Biography information for Joan Ryan","Enfield North","Joan Ryan","29972"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458111","Department of Health","false","2016-03-15","<p>Although no formal assessment has been made of the reduction in the number of people accessing Local Stop Smoking Services in the last five years, Public Health England has been working with local areas, practitioners and experts in the field to better understand the reasons for the reduction in the number of people accessing services and consider how best to continue to help people stop smoking.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2016-03-15T11:21:44.527Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458111/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458111/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458111/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-03-07","Smoking","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment he has made of the reasons for the reductions in the number of people who use Stop Smoking Services in the last five years.","false","Biography information for Mr Jonathan Djanogly","Huntingdon","Mr Jonathan Djanogly","30005"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458112","Department of Health","false","2016-03-10","<p>Reports of suspected adverse drug reactions (ADRs) are collected by the Medicines and Healthcare products Regulatory Agency (MHRA) and Commission for Human Medicines through the spontaneous reporting scheme, the Yellow Card Scheme. The scheme collects suspected ADR reports from the whole of the United Kingdom in relation to all medicines and vaccines. Reporting to the Yellow Card Scheme is voluntary for healthcare professionals and members of the public. There is also a legal obligation for pharmaceutical companies to report all serious ADRs for their products that they are aware of.</p><p> </p><p>The table below provides the number of UK suspected spontaneous ADR reports received via the Yellow card Scheme in association with each drug substance as requested.</p><p> </p><p>The information in the table shows the number of UK spontaneous suspected ADR reports in association with Dabigatran, Rivaroxaban and Apixaban up to and including 7 March 2016.</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Drug substance</p></td><td><p>Number of reports</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Dabigatran</p></td><td><p>1,552</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Rivaroxaban</p></td><td><p>3,291</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Apixaban</p></td><td><p>900</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p>A full list of the type and number of reactions, broken down by the reaction term, is publically available for each medicine on the MHRA website. It is important to note that Yellow Card reports are not proof of a side effect occurring due to the medicine but only a suspicion by the reporter that the medicine may have caused the side effect. Yellow Card reports may therefore relate to true side effects of the medicine, or they may be due to coincidental illnesses that would have occurred in the absence of the medicine.</p><p> </p><p>Dabigatran, rivaroxaban and apixaban are anticoagulant medicines used to prevent or treat blood clots. The most commonly reported adverse reaction for all three medicines is gastrointestinal haemorrhage or bleeding, which is in keeping with the known anticoagulant effects of these medicines. Other relatively commonly reported suspected adverse reactions include bleeding at other sites of the body, gastrointestinal symptoms (such as nausea, pain and diarrhoea), anaemia, and rash. These adverse reactions are described in the product information, in both the Patient Information Leaflet for patients and the Summary of Healthcare Products for healthcare professionals.</p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman",,"2016-03-10T11:16:20.617Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458112/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458112/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458112/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-03-07","Drugs: Side Effects","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many instances of adverse reactions have been reported under the Yellow Card Scheme; and what the nature of the reaction reported was in the case of (a) dabigatran, (b) rivaroxaban and (c) apixaban.","false","Biography information for Paul Flynn","Newport West","Paul Flynn","29973"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458113","Department of Health","false","2016-03-15","<p>The Department has no plans to undertake consumer facing information campaigns in preparation for the introduction of the revised Tobacco Products Directive’s (TPD) requirements.</p><p> </p><p>The TPD introduces a number of new product, labelling and reporting requirements for businesses supplying tobacco products, herbal products and e-cigarettes. The Department has and will continue to engage with businesses to make them aware of the new requirement and has recently held training sessions on the new legislation for enforcement officers. The Department will work alongside enforcement officers to build compliance over the transition period set out in the Regulations.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2016-03-15T11:28:18.957Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458113/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458113/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/458113/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-03-07","Tobacco: EU Law","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what plans he has to undertake consumer information campaigns in preparation for the introduction of the EU Tobacco Products Directive.","false","Biography information for Mr Jonathan Djanogly","Huntingdon","Mr Jonathan Djanogly","30006"
